liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A future hydrogen terminal near Whyalla has secured funding commitments from the state and federal governments, with expectations of "large-scale" global exports before the end of the decade. The state and federal governments have ratified funding arrangements for a so-called "hydrogen hub" at Port Bonython, committing to a combined $100 million spend, in addition to private sector funding. The location, in South Australia's Upper Spencer Gulf region, was earmarked by the previous federal government before last year's election for future hydrogen projects. Among them is what Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has described as a "large-scale export terminal" for "green" hydrogen. The government expects the local industry to produce as much as 1.8 million tonnes of hydrogen by 2030, and said it could also power steel production at the nearby Whyalla steelworks, which is owned by British billionaire Sanjeev Gupta. You can continue reading this story below:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The release of the government's Employment White Paper is the beginning of a "critical conversation" for the country as it looks ahead to the future of the Australian economy, the challenges it will present, and the opportunities that are ahead. Barrenjoey's chief economist Jo Masters told finance presenter Sue Lannin the release of the White Paper is a "really important first step in a critical conversation for Australia". But she says the challenge now will be getting the policy measures right to ensure the White Paper's objectives are achieved. You can watch their full chat below:
